A note about the homework?


if every vector i san eigen vector (except v=0) then the linear map L is a multiple of the identity map

Proof:
    if dim(V) == 1, then every linear map is a multiple of Id.

    Define:linearity


    Suppose dim(V) >= 2
        pick any two lin. indp. vec. v & w. 
        
        Then L(v) = lam(v) && L(w) = mew(w)
            bet(v) + bet(w) = bet(v+w) = L(v+w) = L(v) + L(w) = lam(v) + lam(w)
            (lam-bet)v + (mew-bet)w

            Linear independence implice lam-mew = 0  &&  mew - bet = 0
            hence lam=mew
            This implies a single eigen value L=lam(Id)


    At some point we proved a related theorm 
    if two different eigen values associated eigen vectors are linear independent
    lam1 ... lamk = distinct eigen values, associated with eigenvectors v1 ... vk
    then v1...vk are lin indp


    Linear independence
